  &lt;p id="agrEIT"&gt;DirecTV has &lt;a href="https://www.anrdoezrs.net/links/8532386/type/dlg/sid/verge/https://www.directv.com/insider/directv-and-dish/" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;reached an agreement to acquire Dish TV&lt;/a&gt;, Sling TV, and the rest of Dish parent company EchoStar’s wider TV business, a move that would combine Dish’s roughly 8.1 million subscribers with DirecTV’s 11 million US subscribers, &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/09/30/business/dealbook/directv-dish-merger-deal.html?partner=slack&amp;amp;smid=sl-share"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The New York Times&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt;. The deal is a complicated debt transfer — the transaction price is a single dollar, but DirecTV will assume $9.75 billion of Dish’s debt. The deal serves as a lifeline for EchoStar, which has no means to pay the $2 billion of its overall $20 billion debt due by November 14th.&lt;/p&gt;
